reviewText: Take the leap.  BEST new show IMHO.  I often watched the episodes 2-3 times because I'd be laughing so hard.  Loved the movie In The Loop; Veep does NOT disappoint.  And, I love colourful words; I shan't lie.  Happy next season will be 10 episodes instead of 8, it wasn't enough!  Here's hoping for deleted scenes, et cetera, in the extras.  I'd totally vote for Selina.

I'll tell you what...HBO has done it again! With only an eight episode first season, Veep has got my vote! The show is funny, witty, well acted, and at the end of each short 30-minute episode I'm left wishing the show was an hour. The good news: Veep has been picked up for a second season according to a 4/30/2012 Hollywood Reporter article. Like The Office, the show is shot in that improv, hand-held camera, 'you are there' style of filming, which for me can get a little annoying (especially since filming in that style has been an epidemic of late), but that is the show's only negative in my opinion. The show follows VP Selina Meyer and her bumbling staff as they try to navigate through the brutal behind the scenes world of Washington DC politics. And for the most part poor Selina and her staff find themselves in wayyyy over their heads in almost every situation. The result is the hilariousness that ensues as we watch Selina get herself into one embarrassing and humiliating situation after another, then try to get out of those situations without self destructing. And don't get me wrong about the "bumbling staff" comment...I mean no disrespect to the supporting cast. The chemistry between Julia Louis-Dreyfus and the cast of 6 primary supporting actors (Anna Chlumsky, Tony Hale, Reid Scott, Timothy Simons, Matt Walsh & Sufe Bradshaw) is the key ingredient to Veep's excellence. 4 stars for Veep. Vote this great, hysterical show into your cart!

While the first season isn't the best, it does get better in the second and third season. Sometimes these type of words are used effectively, but in this case, no real reason for it to be used.  Very distracting and VERY disappointing given the star of this show. Having seen Julia-Louis Dreyfus nab several Emmys for her work on Veep, I thought it was time to catch up.  I wasn't disappointed.  Having watched the two seasons on Amazon I couldn't get enough and intend to purchase the remaining three seasons.  The show perfectly captures the intricacies and inanities of our political system and does a great job of skewering politics in general.  Considering the current political climate, this is a perfect detour away from what is very nearly a situation comedy in real life to this better plotted, funnier, and more pointed fictional version.  There aren't a lot of big laughs but there are certainly a lot of small ones and Julia does a terrific job, resisting the fall into slapstick or comedy that's too broad to be real.  A note of caution though: if you object to coarse language steer clear of this one.  The stream of cursing is constant and if there is a criticism of this show by me, it's that.  But putting that aside, a very funny and well-done sitcom.  And maybe this will be my write-in candidate for President this year.

The biggest problem I have is there are no compelling, likeable characters. Everyone is a bit snide.  There are funny moments and I feel it is probably semi-accurate on how bills and other things get done in Washington DC politics, but after watching 3 episodes, I just don't care about any of them and it is going to be more of the same.  The 3rd episode had the Veep character interact with her college age daughter, which continued to show no real human feelings except annoyance, irrigation, fear, self-preservation - none of the characters have any principals, none are idealistic, none have a desire to better the world, etc. and it is not funny enough to survive on the humor alone.  Most of the humor is anxiety humor - can I get through the next crisis, basically.  It is not Cheers, Frazier, RoseAnne, Mash.  It is Seinfeldish, but with much less humor.  I do not know why it has been so top-rated.

I like JLD.  But, as a father of a daughter with down syndrome, I take offense to people who use the word retard or retarded to illicit a laugh.  People who have family and loved ones with mental retardation don't care for it much either.  Whether it is a soldier who receives a traumatic brain injury, someone who tragically contracts an illness, or someone who happens to be born with an intellectual disability, this word causes pain and suffering to those who struggle with intellectual disabilities and those who love them.  But then, that is the world we live in.  Race is off limits unless you are white, sex and sexuality is off limits unless you are a straight man, but somehow we can still make fun of those wonderful folks in society who have to work 5 times harder to do things that most of us take for granted.  Lets not make them feel ashamed and unworthy.  Instead, lets love them and treat them with dignity and respect.  Furthermore, did they have to say f%$K every other word.  Maybe once in a while it can maintain some comedic value for folks who are not offended by it.  But in the 15 minutes we watched it seemed to be used pretty extensively.  Not a fan.  Execs need to find some new writers because the ones you have need to focus on their middle school classes! Watch something else.

You might say my wife and I were late to the party on Veep, since over the years we've been too stingy to add HBO to our cable bill.  So imagine my amazement when, during this first season, there's an episode devoted to the vice president deciding as a PR move to show her transparency by releasing all of her and her staff's email correspondence -- but it's tempered by a scene when Louis-Dreyfus and her staff stand around and candidly discuss embarrassing matters they (of course) must leave *out* when they release said correspondence to the public.  All of this had a very familiar ring to it, so it's a little amazing that season 1 aired 4 or 5 years ago.  And I suppose that's what makes Veep both engrossing and repellent: it wickedly satirizes our federal government with an insider's matter-of-factness that's at once disarming and alarming.  In the end we might as well laugh at the venal sins of our elected officials, because the alternative -- blowing it up and starting over -- is too ghastly to contemplate.

We have two dogs, one named Olive and one named Magic. We will sometimes call our dog Magic, Black Magic because he's a black dog. Both of our dogs are anxious and we have tried for over a year to find a way to distract Olive and Magic when we leave the house for extended periods of time. Up until recently, when we left the house even for a short time, we would receive many complaints from the neighbors about strange noises coming from our house. Our dogs would get so anxious that they would bark, whine, and run around the house making small tapping sounds on the floor. This bothered our neighbors and frustrated us because we would be out having fun and receive a nasty, threatening message forcing us to come home and ruin a fun afternoon or evening out and about. Thankfully, we have found our solution. Veep: Season 1. The comedic antics of Julia Louis-Dreyfus as vice president of the United States thoroughly captivate and engage our dogs attention. While previously they would run around wild being obnoxious, they are now completely engaged in the television. And, thankfully, because we turn Veep: Season 1 on the smart television it plays the first six episodes guaranteeing us at least 5 hours of worry-free time away from home. As for the program itself, I have only seen the first 10-15 minutes but I have seen it everyday for the past few months. From what I've seen, it looks funny and unique. I haven't seen enough to rate it myself but my dogs have never been more well behaved so for that I give it 5 stars.

What a rollicking and interesting look into the life of a reluctant vice president!  The inner working of the political structure of the Executive Branch is most entertaining.  Our Veep is charming, eager, and most attractive--her wardrobe is to die for!  The depiction of the people who surround her and assist her in carrying out her duties really carries this series.  There are those eager to do her bidding whether fetching coffee or running an errand, those who are out to make her look good at all costs, the bleeding hearts who want so badly to do good things for the "folks back home," and those with their pet projects which they pursue at all costs.  The language is a bit rough and I hope that is not the way things are done in DC, but there is enough of the everyday news in this show to keep me watching.

I have always enjoyed Julia Louis-Dreyfus; however, when I discovered the HBO comedy Veep, I quickly came to realize that Ms. Louis-Dreyfus is one of the greatest actors of my generation.  Dare I mention her name in the same breath as Meryl Streep?  I think it is safe to do so. For the people who mistakenly believe that Ms. Louis-Dreyfus plays Julia Louis-Dreyfus, watch her entire body of work--most especially Veep. Watch the emotion she conveys with the slightest of facial movements. Even her nuanced performances are nuanced. Furthermore, I noticed Veep season 1 has less 4-star and 5-star reviews than the subsequent seasons.  Veep season 1 is worthy of 5 stars nevertheless, and the first season sets the foundation for a brilliant series. The other actors are spot-on, well-cast and the perfect ensemble, but Veep belongs to Julia Louis-Dreyfus.  Enough Said. :-)

I gave this show a shot while looking for the next thing to binge watch. It did not hook me. I found it boring from the get go.

It's no single thing that dooms this show. The writing is intelligent. The acting is good. The production value is solid. But somehow it just doesn't all gel together.

I get the plot. I kind of like the characters. I just couldn't find myself caring how any of it worked out. Somehow it felt like watching actual politicians conduct day to day business (which I assume was the goal for the producers) rather than watching a comedy show. Yes, it's funny in places, but it's not enough to sustain the show.

The comedy is in the mundane nuances of politics, not actual jokes. I get why people like it. But it's not for me at all. (Note: The profanity doesn't bother me at all. It should have more. That's always a common thread among low star reviewers that there is too much swearing on any HBO series. Like...hello. The letters HBO should have tipped you off about what would be in the content. When you go to art museums are you shocked that there are so many paintings?)

Okay, I didn't get into "Veep" from the beginning, but I wish I had. My plan is to binge watch my way through to being caught up.  HBO clearly has another hit in its lineup. It's so irreverent and entertaining! (Thanks, HBO, for not adding a laugh track.)
I couldn't give it five stars, though. Though I'm only through two episodes from Season 1, I have heard the "F Word" and all its permutations way more than I ever imagined. If someone thinks the average American resorts to "F..." as frequently as the "Veep" cast, then he, she, or they are laboring labor under a misapprehension. Sheesh, I could barely get through the first episode.  I know it's about politics, so it's no surprise there are a lot of shallow, ambitious characters that don't hesitate to stab each other in the back if it serves their immediate purpose.  But, in addition to the basic mean-ness of the characters being a bit over the top, the real problem is that it just isn't entertaining.  The Seinfeld show was also about a bunch of ethically challenged people, but it was hugely entertaining.  I don't have sufficient critical skills to determine why Seinfeld worked and Veep doesn't, but to me the difference is striking.  Of course, I watched only the very first episode and can't say if it improved after that.  I doubt it, though, and have no intention of watching another episode to find out.

If you readily embrace the 'new morality' that has been growing in public acceptance, and are amused by having mental pictures drawn for you verbally by the non-stop lewd comments, then this is the show for you. If you're offended by such things, then beware. Even though there are a number of amusing situations that come up in the political venue of the series, the Homosexual lewdness is continuously being brought up and pushed in the views face. It is a very large part of what this show is about and I believe to be part of the the indoctrination process going on in entertainment in order to dull the moral senses of the public.

Has some good moments, but feels like "Elaine Benes" character from Seinfeld was actually elected VP.  The level of incompetence & petty in-fighting of her senior staff is also sub-par, but has the same go-nowhere banter as the old Seinfeld series.  It worked with Seinfeld series, as the characters were just ordinary people & so a certain on-going ineptness wasn't going to harm anyone but themselves (for the most part).  If this had been about some corporate exec, or a lower public office (like mayor or congresswoman, etc.), this might have seemed a bit funnier.

But for the person who's a "heartbeat away from being the Most Powerful Person in the Western World", it just doesn't play well.  I watched the entire season, as i think Julia Louis-Dreyfuss has a lot of talent & potential.  I kept hoping that after a few episodes the series would "find its legs" & level out.  Sadly, that was not the case.  Not terrible, but not as good as i had hoped.  In all fairness, this is a comedy (as opposed to The West Wing, The Newsroom, & House of Cards [both American & British versions]), so the level of viewer "mental engagement" is not expected to be as elevated as those series.  But it might have been?  At least, that's what i'd hoped.

That has its place when it appears selectively, but I lost respect for the writers for the semi-automatic barrage of its use as the adjective of perpetual choice.  Perhaps a very young audience thirsts for the word in the same way that they relish the moment that they turn 21 and can legally binge drink. "Last Man Standing" is my benchmark for a 5-star sitcom. If that one is not on your list of favorites you best stop reading now. Veep is NOT un-watchable (that would be one star). Half way through Season 1 Episode 3 we decided we'd given it enough time to trip our trigger even slightly. Sometimes humorous on the rare "surprise" moment (that's part of what makes comedy funny - the unexpected). If I were a twenty-something who'd just shared a doob it might be funnier. It's not the cast's fault...I reckon they do the best they can with the script they're handed. We don't rate it good enough to hang in there through Season 4 and try to figure out how it won an Emmy. Critically acclaimed? Hmmm...those critics must have low standards for a sitcom, but then again, maybe the screenwriter(s) got it figured out after 3 seasons, though I'm unclear why it was renewed for a 2nd season. Maybe the cast and crew agreed to work at half salary? I felt strongly enough about the poorness of this show to write this review, and I have MUCH better things to do with my time.

This show is brilliant, and JLD is criminally under-appreciated by the viewing public. At this point in TV history, it's impossible not to note the great similarities in thesis behind this show and HOUSE OF CARDS, another fine (if much darker) show about the inner workings of Washington, D.C. (and the White House, in particular). That said, VEEP is the stronger vehicle for this project--it's writing is sharper and leaner than HOUSE OF CARDS's and avoids the arch melodrama that occasionally (now, frequently) mars the latter (even though HOC is, indeed, a dramatic vehicle). VEEP knows that the Kafka-esque interplay of power, gender, and politics in government is damn funny at its core, even while showing how deeply alarming it is to consider that "bureaucratic logjam" is the best possible way to describe how the national apparatus works; HOC by contrast takes itself way too seriously. Ambition has a way of organically shaping events, which is reflected perfectly in JLD's Selena Meyer (and far less so in Spacey's arch-villain Frank Underwood). So when you get tired of the doom and sinister overtones of HOC, try a dose of the far more satisfying and illuminating VEEP. You won't regret it, and you'll almost certainly learn much more about how power really works at that level--especially when it comes to the role gender plays in the exercise of that power.

P.S. JLD for president!

Veep Season 1 stars Julia Louis Dreyfus as a zealous and energetic Vice President Selina Meyer who enjoys her job and has many workers surrounding her who keep up on the day to day communications of what goes on in the white house (multiple employees that perform different communications/public relations specialist roles).  One of the scenes involves  the planning around getting ready for a political fundraising event.  There are multiple cultural references as well such as Simon & Garfunkel, The Washington Post, Doogie Howser etc.  Anna Chlumsky plays  as Amy Brookheimer, one of Meyers right hand assistants and I noticed that Kate Burton (from the tv series Scandal) also makes an appearance in Veep.  I admit that Veep Season One, while fictional and based on the idea of Selina Meyer (Julia Louis Dreyfus)starting as Vice President, does underscore from my perspective that I feel that our country is ready for a female president (Hillary Clinton).  Im normally for whoever is the best person for the job (regardless of whether they are Republican or Democrat) but I currently prefer to avoid saying why I prefer to vote for Clinton over who currently looks to most likely win the Republican ticket; Donald Trump (especially since I would otherwise feel like a a hypocrite because I reviewed a book by his daughter Ivanka Trump back in January 2015 before I even knew for sure that Trump was certainly running for president and a Travel & Leisure magazine subscription magazine back in February 23,2011 for the February 2011 Travel & Leisure magazine issue that also featured an article about Ivanka Trump on page 40).

As a longtime Seinfeld junkie I was skeptical at first that "Veep" would be worth watching, but after two episodes I found myself binge watching the rest of Season 1 as well as Seasons 2 & 3, then staying current on Season 4 until the finale.  When I explain the show to others, it's usually "Imagine 'The Office', but taking place at the highest levels of government, with plenty of profanity."  Veep also does a great job of parodying what must be sheer anarchy behind the scenes of any given government official's indiscretions and really play up the "cover stories".  The abundance of one-liners and coined terms is also worth mentioning; although not on par with Seinfeld's "Shrinkage" or "Soup Nazi", Veep uses terms like "FLOTUS" (First Lady of the United States) and "FDOTUS" (First Dog of the United States).  Drawing another parallel with Seinfeld, the cold-blooded tendencies and sheer indifference to the struggles of others are characteristics that almost the entire cast shares in the show, which probably fits in nicely with how the public views politicians in the first place, not to mention there is some first-rate talent playing cabinet members/senators/congressmen.

Bottom Line: Given the time, I would binge watch multiple seasons, over and over again.

Good detail on the set, looks like the real DC White House offices.  Veep and her 'people' are constantly adjusting their positions on the changing situations of real life politics.  There is a hilarious cast of comedic characters, who weave in and out of the frame, interacting with each other on political, professional, and personal planes. Nice change of pace to see powerful women with men serving as assistants and interns instead.  The shallowness of politics, the importance of presentation over substance or morality, is dealt with a light comedic, albeit satirical hand in some scenes.

Julia Drefus is a pleasure to watch, spirited, savvy, smiling and sincere, but with the right Machiavellian mind to steer through the pitfalls of politics at the top echelons.  The cast is equally fun to watch with their antics, idiosyncrasies, and human frailties.  Lighthearted comedy, and fun to watch.  Some of the lines make you chuckle, or laugh out loud.  Very good dialogue!

It's a little too choppy of a show for me, and the characters are extremely volatile toward one another language-wise (which I'm sure is supposed to be funny because they are all under lots of pressure and intentionally don't use any kind of filter when letting out all of their thoughts towards one another).  However, even though I am not a political person, I can detect that there are lots of "politics" going on underneath the surface and the writing is very fast and on point.  For those who savor these kinds of situations that the Veep has to go through and those of the layers of people that surround her, I'm sure there is lots of "tongue in cheek" material to enjoy.  For me, I could take it or leave it, but Julia Louis Dreyfus is always great in her roles and the supporting cast rises to the challenge.

I'd give an extra half star if it was possible. The show starts out trying to get its legs while it's doing some character development. You can tell that they didn't have the chemistry on screen down pat until 2 or 3 episodes in. Once they got going.... it's one of the best political comedies I've ever seen. After (what I felt was) a disappointing run on "Old Chrisitne" Julia Louis-Dreyfus gets back to doing the comedic acting she did best on Seinfeld. The running joke of "did the president call?" just gets funnier each time it's strung into an episode. I truly enjoyed "The Thick of it" which is the British show that "Veep" was based off of. Not all adaptations from across the pond are stellar, but this one is. Similar to the way "The Office" worked out, this show stands on its own. Veep deserves all the awards and accolades it has earned. Though everything revolves around Drefus' character, I'd consider the show to be an ensemble cast at its heart. Perfect casting all around. On an anecdotal note, it's great to see the little girl from "My Girl" grow into a talented comedic actress. Also love seeing anyone from the cast of "Arrested Development" (Tony Hale) in a comedy. Also Matt Walsh is brilliant... and i promise that's the last of the kudos.

This is a more grown up but still deliciously self-centered Elaine from the Seinfeld years. Her face as she gets the news the POTUS may be having a heart attack is a terrific study in glee, unsuccessfully hidden by faux concern.  The supporting cast is terrific. I had no idea Anna Chlumsky (former child star) had such great comedy chops. Her facial expressions are priceless.  Everyone else is great too, from Mike (recognize him from UCB?) to Jonas the slimeball who misses no opportunity to remind everyone he works in The White House. The Veep' secretary Gail is also a great character and her lines are always worth noting.

Anyone who has watched Ianucci's The Thick of it and In the Loop will clearly see that this series is a knock-off. One familiar face, Anna Chlumsky, lends some credibility to the series but, alas she can only do so much with what she's given. Some of the gags used in The Thick of it are recycled here, tweaked a little and then fall embarrassingly flat.
The series would have done better had they began with a convincing looking Vice President and then proceed from there. Unfortunately, Julia Louis-Dreyfuss only looks a little convincing as a Vice President ala Sarah Palin and then the character was set up to behave like an air head. If that was the intent then, they succeeded. If this weren't an Iannucci effort it would have got only one star.

The comedy is very funny and so very different and very original.  We would have enjoyed it more if it didn't use the F word, every other word.  I don't understand why that word has become part of the comic routine.  In watching some of the other original comedies, such as; Mash, Fraser, Will & Grace,  they had good writers that used the situations to create comedy, not the swearing.  Some of the swearing is understandable, to get the point across but, the amount of profanity on the show is insulting.  The situations made us laugh and the Veep herself, is very funny.  Her facial expressions and her ambition comes across and her timing is right on. But the F word, is that what it is like on Capital Hill?  If it is, I feel for them since there are so many other ways to express ourselves than to use the F word.

I kinda discounted the people who told me this was good.  Mainly because after watching a couple episodes of The New Adventures of Old Christine, I didn't think JLD had any range as an actress.  I was picturing a ditzy woman dropping F bombs and a cast of clowns, especially since I knew The Motherlover from Arrested Development was in this..

The entire cast is excellent-- I particularly like the toned down Buster Bluth and Anna Chlumsky.  And I think JLD is very believable as the Veep Selina Meyer.  She has the self awareness of Sarah Palin and the personal warmth and empathy of Hillary.  I have no issue with the profanity, which seems to be the number one reason people give for hating Veep.  Actually, without the over the top vulgarity, you wouldn't even know this was a satire.  The profanity illustrates how those in power conduct themselves with impunity.  If I was involved in politics, I'm sure I could relate to Selina Meyer's comment, "I feel my soul sliding out my a--".

Isn't that a great line?  "No!  It's vulgar and I won't stand for it.  One Star!! Now, Jim Gaffigan and Last Man Standing.  Those are funny shows!"  This is my favorite kind of humor, and I really wish Amazon would have picked up The Onion because so few shows have the right balance of crudeness, irreverence, and intelligence.  4+ stars.

Ironically, I attempted to leave a review for VEEP but it was rejected-- probably for using some masked expletives as an example of the language used in this sitcom.  I've now edited my review in hopes the review will be published.

Haven't screenwriters learned that simply using expletives does not equal comedy? Every few sentences there's an expletive here, and then an expletive there. Interesting how in great sitcom series such as "Seinfeld" or "M*A*S*H*," "Will & Grace, "All in the Family," etc. there were no use of explatives (obviously because public networks would not allow them). Instead, screenwriters dug deep and wrote comedy that was without guile. Lazy writers rely on expletives and violence as a simple means to heighten a situation's intensity. The writing of this series is witless and relies on spineless characters in such low quality situations that I found it painful to watch. I have been a long time fan of Julia Louis-Dryfus and her talent as a comedian/actor is without match; however, her genius is not enough to make VEEP into more than it is- an uninteresting series without creativity. What a waste.

If you awake one day and suddenly find yourself in need of a primer in conversational profanity, look no further than Season 1 of VEEP.  In this vehicle for Seinfeld alum Julia Louis-Dreyfus she plays failed Presidential candidate Selina Meyers whos stuck with the thankless #2 job.  The shows kind of like House of Cards in its cynical portrayal of Washington politics minus the sex, murder, plotting, and scheming but with a comedic twist.
 Louis-Dreyfus is excellent and has matured since her days playing Elaine and looks terrific.  The mostly unknown supporting cast does a fine job portraying a team of sycophants.  The stories involve watching the staff groveling for their high maintenance boss as shes ignored by the POTUS while still trying to make a difference and gain some respect.  The writing is good and there are many funny moments watching these dysfunctionals try to govern our nation.
  Back to the language; having spent four years of my military career in the Army where obscenity  is the lingua franca of the service I personally don't find this show offensive.  I guess in politics, like the Army if you don't punctuate every utterance with the F-word you're just not taken seriously if were to believe this show.  Its not as bad as Deadwood but many will have their sensitivities challenged.  Despite this I recommend VEEP for an snarky take on life inside the beltway.

A skewed, cynical and amusing look at political maneuvering in the White House, VEEP plays to our fears that our nation's leaders are just as bumbling, conflicted and insecure as the rest of us -- only more so.  Julia Louis-Dreyfuss manages to walk the fine line between being likable and despicable.  She's an anti-heroine with a foul mouth and a bucketload of anxieties who, as with many actual vice presidents, got her position after a failed run for the Oval Office.  In Season One, she's fighting to make her mark and craft her legacy while being sidelined from any real power.  The recurring line -- "Did the President call?"  "No." -- is the season's motif.  No one really cares about her except her oddball staff, whose hopes are pinned to the vice president's star.  VEEP made me laugh occasionally, smile frequently, and often wonder how far the parody strayed from reality.

Veep Season 1 starts out a bit slow. I watched with a friend and he was a bit underwhelmed with the first episode and dropped the series. I personally was patient until about episode 3 where I started to enjoy the characters more and the humor was a bit more improved. From there however, the series skyrockets. Julia Dreyfus and Anna Chlumsky are great comedic actresses and both do an OUTSTANDING job. The characters are all annoying and rude, but still likeable for their inability to get off the struggle bus no matter what they do. Tony Hale does a great job but still has some inklings of Buster Bluth from Arrested Development which is kinda great. My point is, be patient and don't expect completely loveable and accessible characters but enjoy the clever humor, the dry delivery, and the hilarity of some very rude people digging themselves deeper into political holes :D

the first episode of this show was not very good, but i persevered and watched a few more before deciding if i liked it or not. i decided i like the show and it is good, but not great.  Julia Louis-Dreyfus does a great job of acting like an idiot, and the characters all play off each other really well.  it is a show that many people may not understand the humor in (like my husband), but i like it.  the type of humor is sort of like the austin powers movies, which i enjoyed, but again, my husband did not.  Dreyfus plays an insulting, gutter-mouthed, crass, controlling, manipulative diva in her role as vice president, and her staff play subserviant, butt-kissing whatever-you-want-me-to-do roles. the show makes you think about how things might actually be in the white house, or with famous people (how they actually act, and interact with other people, and how they get things done or not done).  it is worth a look-see if you like odd humor.  otherwise, pass on it.

There have been several shows recently that have attempted to follow up on the success and poignancy of West Wing in portraying Washington politics, but with a female emphasis. Madame Secretary and Scandal are more substantive examples; by comparison Veep is a shallow show that skirts significance in favor of the quick guffaw. It is difficult to imagine that a politician with such limited insights could be elected to any national office (!?senate?!), let alone serve in the executive branch. Strictly for eminently forgetable humor  do not expect depth or insights.

You can't really fault the actors--the script is just not that funny.  It seems they're trying to tell the same joke over and over, which is that the VP really has nothing to do, but must at all costs look really good doing it. The lines come at a breakneck speed, especially those about the supposed political situations that are coming up, but the writers have done really nothing to make the viewers care about this bill or that person...
Spin City worked because the goofy politician was in charge (Mayor of New York City,)  and his staff had to cover his tracks all the time. VEEP  doesn't work as well, because they start with the premise that the VP is pretty much useless anyway, so what's the point?

It's funny - not overtly political.  It thrives on the miserableness of people we all wind up working with.  The back-stabbing, pettiness, over-reaching ambition - is all there - and very cleverly rendered.  The acting, as an ensemble, is first rate.  These characters feel lived -in from the pilot.  And the dialogue is sharp, surprising, frantic and consistently funny.  It's right up there with His Girl Friday.  The directing is its own extraordinary piece of business.  Multiple moving cameras and angles - nothing about it is visually like a "sitcom".  A super fast paced enjoyable half hour - and now I'm hooked.

It's hard to like the self-important characters of this show.  They are occupying space in Washington, DC, at the expense of taxpayers throughout the country.  Protocol and diplomacy may be called for, but the behind-the-scenes sneakiness and backstabbing comments made by the Veep and her staff were pretty much ugly.  It is a disheartening portrayal of people clawing their way to greater status or importance... having misfounded loyalties to people who are mostly are self-serving and blinded to anything that deters them from their goals.  I guess I have to say I didn't like the subject matter, but the presentation was believable.  I would hope there is more respectful treatment going on than what is in the series... but not so sure that is the case.

I would give it a much higher rating if it wasn't for the quality or lack of same in the writing. One of the problems I've noticed with HBO presentations is that they often will take a really good story such as this one or Deadwood and then diminish it with sloppy writing and gratuitously bad language. Stringing three "F-bombs" together in a five word sentence works against the fine performances of the cast. I have no problem with realistic language that furthers the plot but this series makes me start to believe that the writers are being paid by the "F**k."

Julia Louis-Dreyfus shines when she's at her most self-absorbed here and I think they started to figure that out a few episodes in. The supporting cast is just great, and watching their antics as they try to cover up the Veep's blunders and get out of each other's way is the best part of the show.

Let's watch something that has won some awards was the driving factor.
And the bottom line was that it was totally, totally worth the watch!
Everything about this show (to me anyway) is brilliant.
Writing, directing, acting...even the sets...even the music score...everything is worth noting.
It's the perfect storm of creativity and smarts when you get all the right people together.
And in the case of "VEEP" all the right people are working together.
I know that when you talk about a show there are many, many people involved.
I thank you all but especially I thank all the actors for their incredibly nuanced performances.
Just watching their facial expressions when they deliver their lines alone is worth the price of admission.
Don't get me wrong...the scripts are awesome but the delivery of those words is impeccable.
Everything about this show screams intelligence.

This looked like it it had promise as an interesting story, my wife and I like series with strong female leads. However, we shut it down and deleted the series from our watch list after the first 15 minutes.

It looked like the screen writers had no real ideas how to develop the plot and tried to make up for their lack of writing skills or even basic writing craft it by putting gutter profanity and vulgarity in nearly every line of dialog. Listening to the characters interact was about like reading the dialog written on the restroom stall walls in your average middle school. The leaders of our political parties were portrayed as not even having the skill to cuss like educated people.

I assume that the screen writers were expressing their abject contempt for the political class of people who inhabit  Washington, D.C. but I would expect a more subtle attempt to parody the Pols than making them all talk like middle schoolers trying to sound vulgar. I suspect that the real truth is that the screen writers didn't really know themselves how to cuss in a sophisticated manner.

As a writer myself I feel that this kind of writing is an insult to our profession and whatever network functionary signed off on this series and these scripts should be fired for gross incompetence and deliberately insulting the intelligence of all their hoped for viewers. I hope this isn't a true read on how the networks estimate the viewing taste of their audience, because if it is they despise us and hold us in contempt.

I think you need to sit and watch two or three episodes to really get into this show, it is one of those kinds of shows where you get attached to all the minor characters and their banter and office jabber throughout the series, and the more you watch the more you're hooked. It is a bit fast paced, which I Iike, and I love the character relationships and the complexities of Selena herself. She's really a piece of work in the most entertaining way possible and Julia Louis Dryfus (sorry cannot spell her name) deserves all the accolades she gets from this show. Gary is a riot and I love when he snaps, Amy is flawlessly portrayed and I love the way she only barely recognizes the detriment of her life being consumed by her work and makes vain and passive attempts to make it seem otherwise. She's a force to be reckoned with and I have especially loved her this current season. I like how although the characters are all comrades, there's not really any loyalty there (except Gary) as they all are playing a political game and looking out for themselves. That kind of very real dynamic is portrayed nicely here without making them seem like evil people you hate. You always understand the underhanded things they do and in that sort of a funny way this caricature of American politics almost gives you sympathy for the complexities of the chess game that it is, the constant scratching of backs and deceit.

Selina Meyer is the Vice-President of the United States of America, in theory one of the most powerful positions in the world. In practice, she is a spare tyre kept busy with trivial makework and assigned a staff of dysfunctional backstabbers.

Veep is an American comedy series created by Armando Iannucci, a renowned British comedian and satirist. Veep can be regarded as a companion work to Iannucci's BBC series The Thick of It, which explored the dysfunctional workings of British government via a fictitious government department and the people who run it. Like The Thick of It, Veep has no laughter track and its comedy comes from the situations the characters find themselves in, either through bad luck or through their own ill-conceived actions.

Veep is centred on the character of Selina Meyer, played with aplomb by Julia Louis-Dreyfus (best-known for her recurring role as Elaine on Seinfeld). Meyer is a former Presidential candidate whose failed to make the cut and feels she has been given a powerless role to prevent her being a threat to the President. It's also suggested that the President's wife (who, along with the President, is never seen) hates her, and several storylines revolve around Meyer inadvertently upstaging the President's wife through fashion or headline-grabbing 'cute' moves like getting a dog. Almost every episode features a moment where Meyer asks if the President has called, only to be told no.

The bulk of the comedy comes from Meyer's staff: Gary Walsh (Tony Hale), her neurotic personal aide; Amy Brookheimer (Anna Chlumsky), a well-meaning but slightly inept fixer who ends up taking the fall for some of Meyer's misjudgements; Mike McLintock (Matt Walsh), Meyer's director of communications who, bizarrely, insists that he owns a dog when in fact he does not; Dan Egan (Reid Scott), a new, ambitious and ruthless staffmember who is not quite as smart as he thinks he is; and Sue Wilson (Sufe Bradshaw), Meyer's secretary who seems to regard politics (and almost everything) with bored contempt. Completing the regular cast is Jonah Ryan (Timothy Simons), the liaison with the White House, a fantastically creepy and self-obsessed man specialising in inappropriate behaviour and inventing useless new acronyms (FDOTUS for the President's potential new dog). What makes the show work is that not all of these people are shown to be completely useless (otherwise they wouldn't be in their jobs), but that they prove unable to adapt to rapidly-developing situations. In particular, the older staff-members have no idea on how to deal with blogs and Twitter and spend vast amounts of time obsessed with style and spin rather than the substance of their policies.

Performances are uniformly excellent, with Louis-Dreyfus bringing her A-game and convincing as a politician of ambition and substance whose career has taken an abrupt left-turn into near irrelevance, resulting in frustration and annoyance. This is brilliantly show in a sequence where the President falls ill, so Meyer is called into the White House's emergency situation room, where she is almost overcome by the plush furniture, flashing lights and people treating her like she's the most important person on Earth. When the President recovers, Meyer is dumped back to her previous task, eating yogurt at a dessert store in a futile effort to show how down with the people she is. The gap between the two positions has never quite been nailed so ruthlessly as this. Special mention must also be made to Timothy Simons, who makes his character despicably punchable whenever he appears but you also want to hear what fantastically inappropriate thing he's going to say next. He's the Joffrey Baratheon of the West Wing, though fortunately without the power to execute anyone.

The season has a nicely-developed storyline about Meyer desperately trying to get some policies - any policies - through government to show she's not completely useless. An innocuous tweet about cutlery in the first episode snowballs out of control, taking with it several government bills and congressional hearings, whilst an apparent crisis in Meyer's personal life threatens to upset her career until she dumps it on one of her aides. The story, characters and dialogue are all sharp and very funny.

Compared to the genius of The Thick of It, Veep more than holds it own. Veep isn't quite as knives-out nasty as The Thick of It at its most vicious, mainly due to the lack of a character comparable to Malcolm Tucker (although foul-mouthed Congressman Roger Furlong, who appears late in the season, shows hints that he might go that way). But Iannucci's decision to make the new show stand on its own feet without resorting to his old stand-bys is both a brave one and one that works. There are a few episodes that don't quite gel together and it's arguable if some of the staffmembers would get away with what they do without being fired on the instant, but overall this is a very strong opening season.

Her assistants, are there to feed her every bit of information she needs and to provide the exact shade of lipstick required. Amy, played by Anna Chlumsky, is Meyer's chief of staff, while Gary, played by Tony Hale is Meyer's personal aide. Between them, they help Meyer get through PR disasters and the scheming political animals who want to make her look stupid. Not that she needs any help.

All the while Meyer is scheming to become one of the inside group of the President. She is often not invited to even the most uninteresting of Presidential meetings, and she can never make the big time. VP Meyer is in actuality a smart cookie led astray by her urge to be President. VEEP portrays a very realistic look at the life of a VP in DC. And, t will have you in hysterics much of the time.

Julia Louis-Dreyfus plays the out-of-the-loop VPOTUS who is trying to seem relevant and connected, and who marshals her not-inept but also not-ept staff to keep her head above water in the shark-infested waters of DC.  The characters are about as likable as most people find their actual elected officials to be, which is not at all.

Also, in a Seinfeld-ian way, there's nobody to root for, either, as none of the characters demonstrate any non-selfish motives.  However, neither are the VPOTUS and her staff malevolent, so it's easy to root for them to 'do no harm' in the best way possible.

The writing and acting are impeccable, and if you like this you may want to also try 'In the Loop', a film by the same director.  That film focuses on a mid-level UK politician who finds himself thrust upwards into global political issues without the proper preparation, capabilities, or staff.  If you're American you may want to turn up the subtitles to catch the elegant tapestry of cursing woven by key characters in the film.

Similarly, the language in Veep could also be considered harsh by those offended by vulgarity.  I wouldn't call it gratuitous, because I think it's fairly close to accurate, and if you can endure (or, like me, enjoy) the near-poetic use of vulgarity in context, then you may find yourself enjoying Veep.

"Veep: The Complete First Season"
(HBO, 2013)

This show was both a downer and an uninvolving bore. Like "Boss," this seeks to whet what the producers believe is a bottomless public desire to see politicians and politics not simply mocked, but thoroughly demolished and disrespected. On both shows, every single character is greedy and unappealing, purely venal and self-serving, which is a result -- of course!! -- of their being in politics. "Politics = Bad" is the main -- and apparently only -- message on both shows, it rings hollow and false.  That's even more true on "Veep," because the characters are not only unlikeable, they are also universally incompetent, a bunch of easily-mocked boobs who screw up everything they lay their hands on, including the Vice President as portrayed by Julia Louis Dreyfuss.

Really?  Do we really think that any of these people could have gotten this far in politics by being complete idiots? This kind of blunt, aggressive caricature may be comforting to those of us -- and there are far too many these days -- who see politicians as the lowest of the low, a subspecies incapable of solving even the simplest problem. But it's not very realistic, even in the confines of a comedic farce, and perhaps more importantly it fails as drama, since the entire series is reduced to a one-note joke. I also disliked the overuse of profanity, not because I'm some kind of f***ing prude, but because it diminishes the story and makes the writers seem lazy, rather than clever or shocking. Do we really think that the VP would walk around press conferences and fundraisers swearing at everyone around her?  Apparently there are still a few people who think this kind of language still has some kind of shock value when seen on TV, or that it would be cathartic to see those wicked politicians portrayed as if they were 1950's longshoremen. It's not. It's repetitive and dull, and if they wanted it to be funny, they should have used it more strategically and sparingly. The writing on the show is generally very clumsy: there were some clever turns in the interpersonal relations of the various characters, but the attempts to impose an over-arching plot onto each episode were leaden and forced.

I also strongly dislike the shrill portrayal of human beings as universally stupid and self-serving, and felt the same way about other bleak, nihilistic offerings such as Don Cheadle's "House Of Lies." This brand of turbocharged cynicism may reflect some of what's in the popular culture today, but not everyone in America is a Tea Party member or shares their view of politicians as an evil, subhuman species worthy of tarring and feathering, if not worse.  I think most people go into politics with good intentions but find the system so debased and dominated by the uncontrolled influence of money and lobbyists that it becomes nearly impossible to make progress for the greater good. But the portrayal of our most powerful politicians as sitcom buffoons doesn't really help -- it doesn't even feel that much fun. I found this show to be too dull to watch, a ham-fisted mix of "Seinfeld," "West Wing" and "Gomer Pyle." I'll stick to shows with a little more nuance and relevance, thank you. (Axton)

It is a short miniseries that not only ridicules the office of the vice president but makes it appear that each staff member is incompetent.  The writer uses profanity for dialog and reduces talented actors to nincompoops. It was a shame to take a good subject and give it very little style or meaning. Each character becomes a chess board piece waiting to insert a jibe at either each other or an official in Congress or the White House.  It needed the touch of Aaron Sorkin.

We were a bit disappointed - it was not as comedic a vehicle as we expected for Julia. We're hoping the material will improve & the actors will find their footing. We may rent a few episodes of next season to check it out, maybe not.

Reminds me of The Comeback with Lisa Kudrow, or Web Therapy. Great first season. Can be tough to watch sometimes as things almost never go right for Selena, but highly recommend and enjoying Season 2 as well.
LOL. Quick witted and hillarious! This show is perfectly cast. I hope season three comes out soon. this is a favorite family show

Was looking forward to a new series but after watching the entire first season...and now asking myself for a refund of my wasted life hours back....wow...talk about a piece of junk series.  If the 1st Season is indicative of what is to come, you are better off not bothering.

I thought this was going to be something like Scrubs version of West Wing but it is not even that awful, it is beyond boring...and the language does not help at all.  Most of the other critical reviews pretty much sum up the story lines....walk walk walk....talk talk talk...bitch moan complain....walk talk walk....oh yeah...motor cade here motor cade there....walk talk bitch moan complain.  That pretty much sums up all the storylines....except include lots of foul language as well.

Consider another series that maybe draws you into a real storyline and something more substantial than this tripe.

This was our first Amazon instant video, I hope it was not representative.
The download process started and stopped a number of times.  It took a very long time to complete.  Once the picture finally appeared it was only for an instant and the download bar re-appeared only to stall yet again.  It finally started to play normally but the picture quality was poor and fuzzy.  I'm new to this so it could be our system, but I am really disappointed.  We have no problems with Netflix using the same setup.  I was streaming thru our Roku box.
I purchased 2 episodes of VEEP b/c we had such high hopes, but I wish I had not.  I may not be in the right frame of mind after the download problems but it just seemed like they tried too hard to keep it edgy and the only way they knew to do that was by swearing.
i watch shows on my kindle fire before sleep each night  -this was one of my favorites in comedy category
I live in Washington and it seems to be the way things happen here.  I found it a little repetitious.
Wonderful cast. Each character holds their own and it results in laughs throughout each episode. Terrific pacing and some of the best dialogue on TV.
A biting look at politics with moments of humor - JLD does a great job in the title role and the cast of supporting characters are not always likable.
Watched this and House of Cards alternating.  House of Cards has more intrigue, but needed Veep to break up all the seriousness.  Highly recommended combo.

This show is laugh out loud funny. After the DVDs came in the mail, I watched every single episode over a weekend, nearly back to back. The ensemble cast is hilarious. I don't get HBO, so I can't wait for the next season to come out.

I love this show.  There are so many clever things coming at you constantly.  All of the characters are great and hilariously bizarre.  Julia is an amazing actress, totally believable as a whack-job vice president.  Each episode begs to be re-watched and savored.
The writing is clever and acting good, I only watched one episode so hard to judge the season.  I read that this show got a lot better in later seasons.  Julia Louis-Dreyfus is still great.
My husband and I lost interest in it during the first episode. The "Veep" had lots of veneer but not much personality. Washington "insider" jokes quickly became boring.

This neither reflects reality, nor the facts.
May be partly humorous for those who enjoy profanity in all its forms for the juvenile and immature.

Sharp satire done extremely well.  Julia is spot on as a political animal in the Washington jungle.  Good writing and good acting by the whole cast.  Lauguage is a bit blue as you might expect from a cable series.

Like other work-place shows (Barney Miller - The First Season,Alice: Season 3 - What Are You Doing New Years?,The Office: Season Two, [ASIN:B00005JNEQ Scrubs - The Complete First Season]] and  and Star Trek: The Complete Original Series (Seasons 1-3) [Blu-ray] this one just so happens to be in Washington D.C. There are characters that are built in to despise each other, the guy from 'The White House' is despised by all because he touts his position. Question- Is there any new ground to cover after The West Wing: The Complete Series Collection? They aspire to make this funny, with so much swearing that therer is little to laugh about. When The President has some heartburn the VP is briefly treated very well, that lasts for several seconds. Her coming down from that was worth a laugh. But the rest? One episode is about the possible spreading of a cold and the bad digestive results, ugg. The VP has almost no relationship with her daughter. The VP is divorced and has a dude at her place. What? Is this Scandal: The Complete Second Season? Loaded with political infighting, at one point they accomplish a big goal and then have to retract it. Other issues are to rename a possible hurricane as it is the same name as the VP, getting and naming a dog for the VP, and retracting wrong commments by the VP. Perhaps watching some Benson - The Complete First Season is in order, we have seen a clueless exec already.

This show is fantastic and I can watch all of the episodes over and over again.  The DVDs are worth the investment, even for someone who has HBO Go, because the 8 episodes have 12 commentaries.  I am tempted to give the set 5 stars, but the lack of bloopers/outtakes was very disappointing.  Since I can't give it a 4.5, and it is not perfect, I am rounding down to 4.  I'll still be buying season 2!
This show stunk! The story was weak and the language obscene. We didn't even watch the first one and thew it away.

I love Julia Louis-Dreyfuss and she can be one of the funniest people on earth but not this time.  If you want funny political satire watch the original Yes Minister/Yes Prime Minister.  YPM is about a hapless politician who is controlled by his staff.  VEEP is about a hapless politician that has a staff even more hapless than her.

I was so hopeful for this show but it really let me down.  I am guessing that this show was a what if Sarah Palin got elected.  And I think that is why so many people like it.  I never found her laughable and making fun of her is not funny.  There is so much that is laughable about Washington.  I hope season 2 will get it act together.

Despite the bad review Anna Chlumsky has grown into a competent comedian and Reid Scott of The Big C overcomes, for the most part, this mediocrity.
Ground-breaking political comedy.  Excellent.  As a former Senator's Aide, it is too funny because it is way too true!  Enjoy!

If you like politics you will enjoy this show.  I was very disappointed as I enjoyed Dryfus in both Seinfeld and Old Christine.  I had high hopes for this show.  I didn't even find this show to be funny.  Not recommended.

Let's just dive right in from the start shall we? VEEP is one of the most unfunny shows ever created. Yes, it really is that bad. As I watched the entire first season I think I honestly laughed perhaps once and that was just a small chuckle, not a belly laugh. Having just seen THIS IS THE END and actually finding myself laughing out loud about 15 times in the middle of a theater, this show never inspired that once while sitting in the comfort of my living room. It really is unfunny and displays in so many ways how out of touch Hollywood is with the real world.

Julia Louis-Dreyfuss, an actress who has shown time and time again that she knows how to be funny, stars as the title character, Senator Selina Meyer who has just taken on the role of Vice President. But what she thought would be a position that would provide her with some power and a direct link to the White House ends up being nothing of the sort. Selina is given little more to do than the bidding of the President, helping him to shore up votes he needs for projects while never getting credit or the chance to forward her own ideas.

Through it all she plays the political games where back stabbing is a virtue and keeping a smile plastered on your face while twisting the knife is the norm. This same theme is used quite well with Netflix series HOUSE OF CARDS but here it falls flat.

Meyers has surrounded herself with complete idiots or career builders who are more inclined to take care of themselves than her. Some have the potential to be funny characters but are never given the chance to show it. Instead they seem to think that the more they drop the F bomb the funnier they are. This made me worry about how much input Louis-Dreyfuss had in the scripts as I thought back to the time period when Saturday Night Live became a show that was unfunny...and when she was a cast member. At that time they seemed to tell jokes that they thought were funny but that no one laughed at. I found this series to be much like that.

I had heard this series was funny. I even remember several people involved being nominated for Emmys. After watching it I found my feelings about the Emmys and other awards given in Hollywood to be vindicated. Rather than honor anyone for true talent and ability it seems as though they give out awards for simply being someone they like or for trying to portray anyone they dislike in an unfavorable way. Anyone connected with this show who would win didn't deserve it and should immediately give the award back.

I was stunned to see that a second season of this series has already aired and that a third is on the way. It makes me wonder what shows that delivered pilots to HBO were turned down. Surely there was something else that deserved the funding that this show gets. The only thing this show made me want to do was turn back to television to see if a rerun of SEINFELD was on. Now that show was funny and so was Louis-Dreyfuss when she was in it. Unless the only thing you find humorous is how often and how creatively a person can swear it you won't enjoy this show.

I was only able to sit through the first (pilot?) episode. Ihave never seen a program that was so stupid - even 'Dumb and Dumber' which wanted to depict stupidity. The 'VEEP' was so clueless and potty mouthed that I could not bear to open episode two for fear that I would lose whatever I had eaten earlier. This will go to the garbage heap or perhaps I will sell it back to Amazon although I wonder if they in good conscience can sell it to someone else.....

I don't mind foul language, but do people in government really use the f-word in every sentence?
This show is sometimes funny, but generally the characters seem more like caricatures.

I love Julia as an actress but I feel her talent was undermined by the script which makes this vice president one foul-mouthed woman.
she is not portrayed as a woman who is in charge of her own destiny or who can take care of events by herself.
maybe this is a very realistic picture of our government at work. if so, how depressing.
now I only watched the first episode, so this is truly not an inclusive "know all about it" review.
but the profanity and the lack of a meaningful plot turned me off.
OR I NEVER GOT IT IF I ORDERED IT ---FUNNY SH*T-I LIKED IT-CAN YOU HELP ME SORT THIS OUT??-ANYONE?ELAINE HOW DID YOU BECOME VEEP?
Caught this show on an off chance at a hotel I was staying at and was immediately hooked.  Just finished the season on Amazon and have been recommending it to anyone that'll listen!
Sharp, fast and just plain wrong. A stellar ensemble shines in this darkly sweet workplace comedy. The writing is a gift to both actors and audience.

To be honest, I'd intended to give this 4 stars because,much like its precursor 'The Thick of It', an individual episode can seem a little underwhelming on first view but there is a richness and density that can be appreciated with successive viewings. There are so many lines you don't pick up on first time round, or background details. Veep does expect you, the viewer, to do some of the work.  I've never been so in awe of Julia Louis-Dreyfuss' acting ability - there are some real rewind-and-watch-that-again bits (when she's told the President is experiencing chest pains - what is going on inside her face?!).  This is a decent opening season, what's aired of season 2 seems stronger still.  Season 3 should be a blinder!  I've added an extra star just to balance out those one star reviews by people who have decided they want to be offended by certain commonly used words, then get upset when their wish is granted... ;)

Outstanding. She acts so well and so convincingly. I saw this show with a clear thought that this could be Sarah Palin if McCain had won the elections. Sometimes you look at the show and wonder if it could actually be real. They are not trying to make fun of politics. They are just showing how absurd some of it can be at times!

Based on a rave review by a local entertainment critic, I recently viewed the first two episodes of this series. Unfortunately, I was left with an unpleasant sensation of, "Mayhem, cursing and unfunny jokes." The portrayals of high ranking government officials and their aides come across as cartoon caricatures. The hand-held camera also makes for a jerky production and may induce vertigo in some viewers. Most damning, none of the political material seems particularly topical or relevant. Needless to say, I wouldn't go out my way to watch this one

Initially I was attracted to this show because of Tony Hale and his beloved role as Buster on Arrested Development. Then I remembered Julia Louis-Dreyfus has the blind attorney on AD as well and I couldn't resist. All the situations they find themselves in are hilarious.
A friend recommended this and I was not disappointed. LOVE Julia Louis Dreyfus and the rest of the cast. Great writing and actors, SO funny !
I cannot wait for more episodes! Very well written dialogue and some potentially too true to life scenarios in our dysfunctional federal behemoth in D.C.

JLD finally has a vehicle worthy of her talents. Fast, hilarious, and believable whether or not you like politics.
Nice casting and great dialogue.

Even though there were funny and profound moments in VEEP, it was inconsistent and a bit of a disappointment.

Julia is superb, but you have to wade through a little too much vulgarity and crudeness to get to the good stuff.

I would view more episodes if it were free, but not interested in spending more money on it.

Does anyone just love this show and find it worth the money?

This is a show with a very good cast and some really weak writers; a lot of the jokes border on some old material from the Larry David show "reworked" for a "political" show.  A real shame because this show does have it's moments where it is funny.  IMHO too many "tall" jokes regarding "Jonah" but the character "Dan Egan" seems to have some nicely writen material playing a Machevelian staffer.

My main critical comment regards a lot of HBO content; too much profanity!  Now, I am retired from the military so "frank language" is still a bad habit I am trying to break.  In show business however HBO makes a critical mistake with hit shows not looking four or five seasons down the road.  Example, the "Soprano's" and "Deadwood" were just great shows and people who didn't care for the language could vote with the remote.  However, the "Boston" version of the Soprano's is a little silly with all the "freaking" and other sorry measures made to clean it up enough for cable.  As to Deadwood, if a "Boston" version was ever cut for syndication the show would go from an hour to maybe a three minute show the profanity was so bad.  For those of you who are younger, the "Boston" version was a term that came from burlesque meaning that while in Boston you had to clean up the act to prevent a raid.

Returning to HBO, they would do well to bring in some writers who don't have to go for the crouch to get laughs.  This could be a very funny show.  They need to clean up the language.  I am a big fan of the A&E franchise "Breaking Bad"; this is a show about drug traficing, killing and manufacturing meth and with the brilliant writers Vince Gilligan, Executive Producer brings to the script they won't have to produce a "Boston" version.  With the dark subject matter coupled with the gallows humor this show exhibits they won't have to clean it up for cable.  HBO will come to the realization that great writers can create quality drama and comedy and stay out of the gutter.

Great characters, snappy writing and hilarious!  I love the saucy language.  Julia Louis-Dreyfus plays it just right - you start to cheer for her and then she is utterly self absorbed and super ambitious but always, always fallible.
Not really funny stressful to watch and made no sense story line could have been intresting poor acting and had no point. I like a comedy that either makes you crack up or has a point.
I bought the whole season and could only make it through two shows. Not funny. Caustic, cynical and a waste of time and money.

Funny show, but could have been better (probably much better.....if we look at current politics.....)
I like Julia and her fans won't be disappointed....

this series is snarky, biting and funny. Fast-paced and witty. The West Wing married to The Office.  Love Julia and the whole cast - all very well-cast and endearing in a irresistible, human way. They are all a little desperate, as I would imagine people in that high-powered environment would be. They've made it to the almost-top and are a little on edge to remain there and hopefully advance.  Some are looking for backs to stab as others are peddling as fast as they can to stay alive. "Did the president call?" is the Veep's eternal plaintive cry.

This is a smart and funny show. Julia Louis-Dreyfuss is hysterical in this role and is surrounded by an equally funny cast. I re-watched recorded episodes over and over and still laugh through entire episodes. Love this political satire. So true to human emotions and actions.

A very funny show.  It does take a little time to adjust to the foul language coming from Julia's mouth, can Elaine really be saying those things, but the language is usually put to good effect.  A strong supporting cast adds greatly to the comedy being presented here.  Republican or Democrat you will laugh at Vice President Selena Meyers  and be absolutely convinced that she is from the Party you do NOT support.

i love julia louise deyfus in "the new adventures of old christine" . i had high hopes for "veep" . a total disappointment. i don't know if the show is a comedy or
drama in any case it fails or both points.i watched 21/2 episodes, couldn't stomach any more. will
trade back into amazon

With a great cast, a fresh wiew on Washington and actually some warmth, Ianucci describes perfectly how it feels to not quite make it. I have to watch this several more times to scoop up all the nuances.
I can't wait for the coming seasons!
We watched this in one weekend and loved it, made us order HBO for the second season.  JLD is hysterical as is the whole cast!

love julia louis dreyfuss she makes the show.

when its funny its incredibly funny but just wish there were more of those moments/episodes

the humor does begin to build on itself over time but there's still a lot of slack in the writing looking forward to see if they tighten it up in season 2

I thought that she had peaked with Elaine on Seinfeld. I didn't think writers could match her energy and wit. This is my favorite show in a long time. I am particularly fond of the ingenious uses of the F bomb and other obscenities. It somehow never gets old seeing grown men and women whose serious jobs dealing with serious issues require them to look squeaky clean on the outside but who behind closed doors cuss like erudite sailors. It's farce of the highest order.

This show is almost too good! Julia Louis-Dreyfuss was born to play this role, a stark contrast to her forgettable sideshow role on Seinfeld. She is believable and her acting effortless. The supporting characters also bring a lot to the table in this lighthearted look at how Washington works.
The only criticism is there are only 10 episodes a season! Come on! Modern Family has 24.
Oh and get the Blu-ray version because they throw the kitchen sink in with it (a free DVD and downloadable version)

This show was OK but not as sharply witty as Seinfeld, as my expectations a series with J L-D would be.  Don't think I will be buying the Second season, at least not until I have seen a good few reviews.
What can one say these days? Politics has become even less reputable, if that were possible. And apparently it is.

After reading some reviews, and being a fan of JLD, I decided to watch the first season of Veep, and I was not disappointed.  I got my share of slapstick and wit.  The writing is superb and the performances by every actor are top notch; they each have their own little quirks that separate them, yet they are so real and relatable.

All the one star reviews here seem to revolve around the use of the "f-word" on the show, well to that I say "seriously?"  The show is a satiric comedy on HBO, this comedy's f word equals showing breasts and a penis on an HBO drama.  Its just a word, one that many people use everyday, and I'm sure that people in government use it too, obviously not when giving public addresses, but behind the scenes(which is what this show portrays more often than not) I'm sure they use it more often than they'd like to admit.

Bottom line, this show is smart and witty humor that can go crude at times, but it only aims to increase the comedic value of the piece and show us a side of Washington that we don't see, and maybe one that we would not even want to imagine, but one that is very, very funny.

I had so much hope I would get a bit of a glimpse at Seinfeld's Elaine, but no cigar. Although Dreyfus is good in this show, It was not the humor I like. Dry, political...blah! You must like Politics to appreciate the humor in this show.
Too much cussing and not enough good story lines. This was disappointing because my husband and I really were looking forward to it.
DONT USE THE F WORD IN SHOWS.  I always liked Julia Dreyfus but this was beneath her. I find shows that have to use the F WORD offensive. Not that good of a show anyway and that just makes it worse.

It would be a funny show except for all the :f bombs" thrown. I used to like her but for her to play in a show with such filthy language is discouraging.
I will not watch any more of this season

Veep is the US remake of British political satirical show The Thick Of It. it's slick and funny and mostly written by the original show's writers'.That said it's much less savage it tone,and lacks the quality of the UK show. It reminds me of the old show Spin City.
Funny and absurd. It's like Elaine from Seinfeld became VP. I hear even Joe Biden watches it. Three more words

I'm sorry Julia, I didn't laugh once watching the first episode. After the first 2 minutes every other word was the F word. If I want to hear the F word that many times I would just put a tape (digital) recorder in my shirt pocket and listen to it every half hour. I'm glad I just tested the first episode on Amazon rather than just buying the entire DVD season at Wal-Mart for the very un-Wal-Mart price of $24.95
Julie Louis-Dreyfus at her best!! Couldn't stop watching after the first episode! Will definitely be tuning in for Season 2.
Very funny look at the behind the scenes of Washington-probably more true to life than we know.  Julia Louis-Dreyfuss is perfect in her role.

I watched half of the first episode. Unlikable characters saying unfunny things to other unlikable characters. I could hardly give less of a damn. I loved The West Wing and thought I'd enjoy this... thing. I didn't.

I just watched the first episode, and I have to say it's not in a class with The New Adventures of Old Christine.  Julia Luis Dreyfus does well as an intimate and complex character.  In this role, so far, she's overcome by the chaos around her.

I'm hoping that as I watch further episodes and her character opens up, I'll see more of the spontanaity that makes her one of my favorite comic-actresses.  I identified with Christine from the first scene of the first episode.  Right now, I'm looking at a character who is over-powered by her surroundings to the point that she almost disappears at times.

We'll have to see...I always have my Seinfeld and Old Christine reruns, but she's a person I like to identify with on many levels.  I don't identify with politicians...

I had read some good reviews about this show and rented the first disk.  It only took a few seconds of the first episode for me to get it.  Total garbage.  I had wasted my money and brought garbage into my home.  I skipped forward and found more of the same.  It didn't get any better.  It's their spin on politics.  Nothing but pacing around offices, walking up and down hallways, and endless talk, talk, talk, talk.  Nothing meaningful or important, and absolutely nothing funny.  Just a lot of childish insecurity, finger-pointing, mud-flinging, back-stabbing, insults, anger, rudeness, fear, and blame.  I don't consider that entertainment.  It's old, it's over, and it's boring.  I can turn on any so-called news channel and hear the same thing 24/7 minus the profanity.  Don't waste your time or money.

I must say that this is my favorite show of all time. I liked "In the Loop" and "The Thick of It" and I LOVE this show!! Timing, writing, acting are superb and this is my kind of funny. I know it might not be for everyone, but this is exactly the kind of comedy that I feel is lacking in America. I'm so glad that they decided to make it here and that they cast such amazingly funny actors. Truly a gem!

Oh dear lord, this series could not be more awful.  It's like the writers started the script writing sessions by generating a list of the most awful profanities they could conjure and then agreeing that the obvious best way to do things was to put at least one in every spoken sentence and that the actors decided that the best way to deliver the lines was to either shout them at one another or to utter them with no expression at all.  Really really awful. In the last episode I tried to watch, one character referred to another as 'bleached anal hair' which, let's be honest, could have been funny but just wasn't.

I'm not against the profane - honestly, I quite adore it, but this was profane instead of anything else.  Just dumb and gross and silly.

25 minutes into 1st episode and haven't even cracked a smile, let alone laughed. Is this a comedy? Chaotic, badly written, no coherent dialogue, terrible unauthentic acting, and simply UNFUNNY.  It was painful to watch. I felt obligated to watch it to the end since I paid for it, but couldn't even sit through a half hr. I love even a mediocre comedy, that makes me feel even slightly amused. This show wasn't even a tiny bit entertaining, it is an unmitigated disaster.

Imagine a less neurotic Christine (from the New Adventures of Old Christine) and a more intelligent and self-aware Sarah Palin (just minus the bats*** crazy Tea Party politics) and you get Selena Meyer, Vice President (VEEP). Julia Louis-Dreyfus is hilarious!

Veep is definitely the best Louis-Dreyfus vehicle since Seinfeld, but that's not saying much.

She is perfectly cast as VP Selina Meyer, as is everybody else in the talented ensemble cast. The problem is the writing. Each episode crams two or three political (or occasionally personal) catastrophes into the less-than-30-minute slot, so there's practically non-stop angst and frenzy as they try to put out the fires. It gets tiring fast.

The catastrophes blow by so quickly that they are practically indistinguishable from one another, and every one gets resolved in some random way that never makes any more sense than the problem did. It's like slapstick without pratfalls and pies in the face. It's just frantic, meaningless running around, packed with non-stop texting and snide put-downs flying in every direction, but it's never funny at all.

Whatever entertainment value Veep has lies only in seeing gifted actors working well together at the speed of lightning; but the awful material they have to work with, and the frantic pace required to fit all that awful material into a half-hour show, make it hard - maybe impossible - to stay with for more than a few seemingly identical episodes.

I guess what I'm saying is that Veep (unlike Seinfeld) is just another frantic, mindless, infinitely repeating formulaic sitcom in the I Love Lucy line, but with snarky wisecracks instead of pies. It's disappointing that that tired formula still thrives in this century.

I'm surprised Veep was renewed for a second season, but I guess I shouldn't be. Maybe they'll hold on long enough to find better writers.
