Very funny show, understated comedy and humor.  The VP is a clueless character, with bumbling (yet hilarious) staff surrounding her. Julia Louis Dreyfus is perfection!

This is a cast of Big Guns with an improv flair and skewering faux pas'. Julia is perfect at portraying a blundering VP (like someone SO familiar!) with an entourage of sycophants that add an incredibly rich backdrop to the whole political and human drama, which makes such great comedy, of life at the White House. So very funny and yet still very fresh! Love it!!! Very irreverent, however, so you've been warned!

I haven't been this excited about an HBO half-hour comedy since 2004's The Comeback, and I'm glad HBO has granted Veep a second term. Veep and The Comeback have a lot in common: treasured NBC sitcom actress playing someone with no self awareness, uncomfortable situations involving body fluids, and ease at mixing small laughs with big LOLs. Veep has a faster pace, which is fitting given that it's about politics. They are dealing with situations non-stop, and the rapid-fire dialogue is fun and frenetic. Julie Louis-Dreyfus is stellar at both the over-the-top explosions and the few quieter moments interspersed between. While there are plenty of uncomfortable situations, they're less cringe-worthy than many in The Comeback, mainly because of the Veep's staff racing around like maniacs to correct the problems and support her, while Valerie Cherish was often left in the open, with a spotlight on her, humiliated. The supporting cast in Veep is all phenomenal, especially Anna Chlumsky (welcome back, My Girl!) playing the thankless role of the Vice President's chief-of-staff, a real-life thankless role. Almost every episode involves a total disaster plaguing the vice president, as her staff races to get things back on track with the public (The president himself? Never seen, and never cares. Every episode, "Did the president call, Sue?" "No.") The constant screw ups make it seem like Selina and her staff are incompetent twits. It's easy to compare Selina to that other female almost-VP Sarah Palin, and write her off as a total twit, but Selina and her staff are not stupid. They're smart people who are totally unprepared for the situation they're in. Being Veep is a whole different game than they're used to. And yes, politics is all just a game. It doesn't help that Selina has surrounded herself with yes-men for twenty years in politics and has absolutely no introspection whatsoever. The true brilliance of Veep is that it manages to do what it does without using either the term "Democrat" or "Republican." As I said, politics is a game, and Veep shows us that *all* politicians, whether left or right, are playing for one team: their own. And we're the losers.

The creator of the UK's THE THICK OF IT also created this show. So he had to take a dry British wit yet wacky show idea and come up with a way to convert it to American politics. This is mostly successful but I suspect the second season will be the one which is the critical test because this season steadily improved as they warmed up.

In the UK show everyone is inept, except for Malcolm, the power behind the PM, and almost everyone is not likable. Taking unlikable characters and making them funny is very difficult but the UK show succeeds.  In the USA the most successful comedy shows featuring unlikable characters were SEINFELD and CURB YOUR ENTHUSIASM, by the co-creator of SEINFELD, Larry David.  So it should come as no surprise that the creator picked Julia Louise-Dreyfus, who played the unlikable Elaine in SEINFELD, to play the veep. If you compare the Veep to Malcolm in the UK show though, there is no comparison.  The veep is likable in comparison.

Dreyfus is supported by a very able cast but this show will rise or fall based on her execution of a Veep who would like to be President and we can only hope she doesn't succeed!  I will be tuning in for season two.  I frankly think she can pull it off in the second season and I am looking forward to her totally unleashing her comedic power in it.
